Slide 16 — Experiment 03 Config

"Experiment 03 goes back to Cross Entropy and Smooth L1 — the same losses as Exp 01 — but switches the optimizer to AdamW with a much lower learning rate of 0.0001.


Why AdamW? SGD with momentum is great for training from scratch, but for fine-tuning pretrained weights, adaptive optimizers sometimes converge faster because they adapt the learning rate per parameter. Parameters that don't need much updating stay stable, parameters that do get larger gradients get pushed more.


The lower LR — 0.0001 vs 0.002 — is necessary because AdamW's adaptive scaling already amplifies effective step sizes. Using 0.002 with AdamW would be aggressive.


AdamW specifically — versus plain Adam — adds proper weight decay decoupled from the gradient update. This is important for fine-tuning: we want regularization on the weights without it interfering with the adaptive gradient scaling.


The comparison this gives us: Exp 01 vs Exp 03 isolates optimizer choice with everything else equal. Exp 02 vs Exp 01 isolates loss function choice. Together, all three tell a clean story."


